 for bestpractices and # User Authentication Prompt for AI Development Tool

Overview:
Build a secure, scalable User Authentication system for LifeOps that supports email/password signups, social OAuth, SSO, JWT-based sessions, and RBAC. Include comprehensive frontend pages (Login/Signup, User Profile, Email Verification, Password Reset) and robust backend APIs with proper data models, security measures, auditing, rate limiting, and brute-force protections. All code must guard against null/undefined values before using array methods, initialize arrays with proper useState defaults, and follow the runtime safety rules explicitly outlined.

Project Metadata:
- PROJECT CONTEXT: LifeOps — Multi-Agent AI Operating System with audit trails, run artifacts, and a Cronjobs system. All auth events must be auditable, reversible, and permissioned.
- TARGET FEATURE: User Authentication
- Associated Pages: page_auth_login_002, page_auth_password_reset_003, page_auth_email_verify_004, page_profile_005
- Design System: Provided in detail (dark UI, specific color palette, typography, spacing, and component behavior)

# User Authentication

## Overview
Implement a secure, flexible authentication system that enables:
- Email/password signups and logins with strong password hashing (bcrypt/argon2).
- Social OAuth (OAuth 2.0 / OpenID Connect): Google, GitHub, Microsoft.
- Enterprise SSO (SAML/OIDC-based as applicable) with seamless user provisioning.
- JWT-based sessions with secure cookies or storage strategies (short-lived access tokens, refresh tokens with rotation).
- RBAC at resource/module level with audit logging for auth events and admin actions.
- Rate limiting, brute-force protection, and robust token lifecycle management.
- Clear onboarding flow and user onboarding wizard during signup.
- API endpoints and pages aligned with provided page names and semantics.

## Components to Build

- Frontend Components & Pages
  - UnifiedAuthEntry (LoginSignupShell)
    - Email/password sign-up and login forms with real-time validation.
    - Password strength meter integration.
    - Onboarding wizard steps (stepper: account type, preferences, onboarding tasks).
    - Social OAuth buttons for Google, GitHub, Microsoft.
    - Enterprise SSO (redirect to IdP) toggle with helpful guidance.
  - LoginPage (page_auth_login_002)
    - Email/password login form with “Forgot password” and “Remember me.”
    - Social OAuth buttons and Enterprise SSO access links.
    - Client-side rate-limiting feedback for failed attempts.
  - SignupPage (page_auth_login_002)
    - Email/password sign-up form with password strength indicator, terms acceptance, onboarding wizard integration.
    - Optional invitation code or domain restrictions for enterprise onboarding.
  - PasswordResetPage (page_auth_password_reset_003)
    - Request reset form (email), sending a time-limited reset token.
    - Token verification screen (with token from URL) and password reset with strength meter.
  - EmailVerificationPage (page_auth_email_verify_004)
    - Verification link handler, show success/failure UI with next steps and retry option.
  - UserProfilePage (page_profile_005)
    - Personal information management (name, email, contact), connected integrations, security (2FA enablement), API keys management, billing summary, and module preferences.
    - Session management (view active sessions and revoke).
  - RBACAdminUI (optional helper for admins)
    - Manage roles, permissions, and resource access controls with audit trail references.
  - AuditTrailPanel (shared)
    - Show recent authentication events, admin actions, and run artifacts for traceability.

- Backend APIs & Services
  - Auth API
    - POST /auth/signup
    - POST /auth/login
    - POST /auth/logout
    - POST /auth/refresh
    - GET /auth/me (current user)
    - POST /auth/logoutAllSessions
  - Social/OIDC/SSO
    - GET /auth/oauth/{provider}
    - GET /auth/oauth/{provider}/callback
    - GET /auth/sso/initiate
    - POST /auth/sso/complete
  - Password Reset & Email Verification
    - POST /auth/request-password-reset
    - POST /auth/verify-reset-token
    - POST /auth/reset-password
    - GET /auth/verify-email?token=...
  - Email Verification
    - GET /auth/verify-email/:token
  - RBAC & Admin
    - GET/POST/PUT /admin/roles
    - GET /admin/permissions
  - Profile & Preferences
    - GET/PUT /profile
    - POST /profile/api-keys
    - DELETE /profile/api-keys/:keyId
    - POST /profile/2fa/enable
    - POST /profile/2fa/disable
  - Billing & Integrations (read-only for UI, or lightweight endpoints)
    - GET /billing/summary
    - GET /integrations/connected
  - Audit & Logging
    - POST /audits/log-auth-event
    - GET /audits/events
  - Security / Tokens
    - JWT signing keys management (RS256 recommended)
    - Token rotation for refresh tokens
  - Rate Limiting & Brute-Force
    - Implement per-IP and per-user rate limits on login endpoints
  - Data Protection
    - Password hashing with bcrypt or argon2 (salted)
    - Secure storage of tokens (httpOnly, Secure cookies) or secure client storage as per platform

- Data Models (Database Schema)
  - User
    - id (UUID)
    - email (unique)
    - passwordHash
    - name
    - emailVerified (bool)
    - preferredLanguage, locale
    - createdAt, updatedAt
    - lastSignInAt
    - active (bool)
  - UserProfile
    - userId (FK to User)
    - phone
    - avatarUrl
  - UserRoles / RBAC
    - id
    - userId (FK)
    - roleId (FK)
    - scope (resource/module-level or global)
    - assignedAt
  - Role
    - id
    - name
    - permissions: array of permission strings
    - scope
  - Permission
    - id
    - name
    - resource
  - Session
    - id (sessionId)
    - userId
    - jwtId (jti)
    - createdAt
    - expiresAt
    - lastUsedAt
    - userAgent
    - ip
    - deviceInfo
  - RefreshToken
    - id
    - token
    - userId
    - jwtId
    - createdAt
    - expiresAt
    - revoked (bool)
  - 2FA
    - userId
    - secret
    - enabled (bool)
    - recoveryCodes[]
  - PasswordResetToken
    - id
    - userId
    - token
    - expiresAt
    - used (bool)
  - EmailVerificationToken
    - id
    - userId
    - token
    - expiresAt
    - used (bool)
  - AuditLog
    - id
    - userId
    - action
    - resource
    - timestamp
    - details (JSON)
  - ApiKey
    - id
    - userId
    - key
    - name
    - createdAt
    - lastUsedAt
    - enabled (bool)
  - Billing
    - userId
    - plan
    - status
    - nextBillingDate
  - Integrations
    - id
    - userId
    - provider
    - connectedAt
    - metadata (JSON)

- API Endpoints & Methods (Routes)
  - Authentication
    - POST /auth/signup -> 200 with user, tokens
    - POST /auth/login -> 200 with tokens
    - POST /auth/logout -> 200
    - POST /auth/refresh -> 200 with new access token
    - GET /auth/me -> 200 with user profile
  - Password & Email
    - POST /auth/request-password-reset -> 200
    - POST /auth/verify-reset-token -> 200
    - POST /auth/reset-password -> 200
    - GET /auth/verify-email/:token -> 200/400
  - OAuth / SSO
    - GET /auth/oauth/:provider -> redirects to provider
    - GET /auth/oauth/:provider/callback -> process OAuth login
    - GET /auth/sso/initiate -> start enterprise SSO flow
    - GET /auth/sso/callback -> finish SSO
  - Profile & Settings
    - GET /profile -> 200
    - PUT /profile -> 200
    - POST /profile/api-keys -> 201
    - DELETE /profile/api-keys/:id -> 204
    - POST /profile/2fa/enable -> 200
    - POST /profile/2fa/disable -> 200
  - Billing & Integrations
    - GET /billing/summary -> 200
    - GET /integrations/connected -> 200
  - Admin / RBAC
    - GET /admin/roles -> 200
    - POST /admin/roles -> 201
    - PUT /admin/roles/:id -> 200
  - Auditing
    - POST /audits/log-auth-event -> 201
    - GET /audits/events -> 200
  - Security
    - GET /healthz / readiness checks

- Security & Validation
  - Passwords stored with bcrypt (or Argon2) + per-user salt
  - Email verification and password reset tokens are time-bound and single-use
  - JWT access tokens short-lived (e.g., 15 minutes) with rotation via refresh tokens
  - Secure HttpOnly cookies for tokens where appropriate; alternative safe storage with proper CSRF protection on SPAs
  - Implement CSRF protection for state-changing requests when using cookies
  - Role-based access control (RBAC) enforcement at API layer for resource access
  - Audit logging for all auth events: login, logout, token refresh, password reset, email verify, 2FA changes, admin actions
  - Rate limiting: per-IP and per-user, to protect login and sensitive endpoints
  - Brute-force protection with account lockouts or progressive delays
  - Input validation: strict schema validation on all inputs, with defaults to prevent undefined/null usage

- Validation & Safety Rules (Runtime)
  - Supabase-like results: use data ?? [] wherever a query returns potential null
  - Guard array operations: (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : []
  - Initialize React state for arrays: useState<Type[]>([])
  - API response shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
  - Optional chaining: use obj?.prop?.subprop when handling nested objects
  - Destructuring with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}
  - All API data shaping must defensively handle null/undefined values

- Integration & Flow
  - Frontend <-> Backend
    - Sign-up/login flows trigger token issuance; store access token in secure storage per platform considerations
    - On successful login, fetch user profile and RBAC roles; enforce client-side route guards and server-side checks
    - OAuth/SSO flows redirect back with authorization codes or tokens; server exchanges codes for user sessions
  - Profile & Security
    - Users can enable 2FA using TOTP (Google Authenticator/Authy) with QR codes
    - API keys management tied to user accounts with revocation and auditing
  - Audit & Observability
    - Each auth event creates an audit log entry with userId, action, resource, timestamp, and details
  - Data Privacy & Compliance
    - Sensitive data token rotation and secure storage
  - Accessibility
    - All forms and controls labeled properly; keyboard accessible

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Use React (or framework of choice) with TypeScript for strong typing
- State Management
  - Use useState/useEffect and context providers for auth state
  - Initialize arrays as [] and ensure types are enforced
- Components & UI
  - UnifiedAuthEntry: orchestrates sign-up, login, onboarding wizard, and transitions
  - LoginPage: email/password fields, social OAuth buttons, SSO link
  - SignupPage: onboarding wizard steps, terms acceptance, validation
  - PasswordResetPage: two-phase flow (request and set new password)
  - EmailVerificationPage: verifies token and shows outcome
  - UserProfilePage: profile editing, 2FA, API keys, billing, integrations, module preferences
  - Dashboard Integration: ensure components receive user RBAC context to render appropriate UI
- Data Handling
  - Use data ?? [] when mapping over server-fetched arrays
  - Validate API responses with Array.isArray(...) before .map()
- Security UI
  - Don’t expose raw tokens in UI
  - Show password strength meter; enforce password rules (min length, complexity)
  - Show 2FA status and setup flow clearly
- Accessibility & UX
  - Clear focus states, aria labels, and error messaging
  - Onboarding wizard supports back/next, progress indicators, validation on each step
- Error Handling
  - Graceful error messages with actionable next steps
  - Retry mechanisms for transient network errors
- Localization
  - Prepare for i18n if applicable (strings externalized)

### Backend
- Tech: Node.js/Express or NestJS (or equivalent) with TypeScript; or your preferred stack
- Security
  - Password hashing: bcrypt (or argon2) with proper salting
  - Token management: JWTs with RS256 keys; rotate refresh tokens; store in secure, HttpOnly cookies or secure storage
  - 2FA: TOTP with secret provisioning and recovery codes
  - Email verification and password reset tokens: secure random tokens with expiration
  - SSO/OAuth: implement OAuth2/OIDC flows for Google, GitHub, Microsoft; support enterprise SSO (SAML/OIDC)
  - RBAC: roles, permissions, and resource-level scoping
  - Audit logging: comprehensive events for auth actions and admin operations
  - Rate limiting: middleware-based throttling (per IP and per user)
  - Brute-force protection: exponential backoff, temporary account lockouts
  - Input validation: strict DTOs/schemas (e.g., using zod/joi/validator)
- Data Model
  - Create schemas per above (User, Session, RefreshToken, 2FA, PasswordResetToken, EmailVerificationToken, AuditLog, ApiKey, Role, Permission)
  - Use null-safe accessors and defaults when querying
- Endpoints
  - Implement the routes listed above with proper authentication guards
  - Return validated shapes: ensure data ?? [] is used for array responses
  - Implement error handling with standardized error payloads
- Integrations
  - OAuth providers configured with client IDs/secrets
  - SSO endpoints and metadata retrieval
- Testing
  - Unit tests for token issuance/verification, password reset flows, 2FA, RBAC checks
  - Integration tests for login, signup, OAuth callbacks, email verification
  - Security tests: token theft, CSRF, rate limits, login attempt throttling
- Observability
  - Structured logging for auth events
  - Metrics: login attempts/sec, success rate, token refresh frequency
- Reliability
  - Idempotent operations for verification flows
  - Idempotent token creation and consumption
  - Idempotent user provisioning from SSO

### Integration

- Authorization Workflow
  - On app boot or session restoration, fetch current user and RBAC roles, then set global auth context
  - All protected API routes enforce RBAC by validating user roles/permissions
- Token Lifecycle
  - Access Token: short-lived; used for API authorization
  - Refresh Token: long-lived but stored securely; rotate on use
  - Attempt to renew tokens via /auth/refresh; on failure, redirect to login
- Email & Password Flows
  - Signup triggers email verification if required
  - Password reset triggers time-limited tokens and UI flows to reset
- OAuth/SSO Flows
  - OAuth callback handles code exchange, user provisioning, and session initialization
  - Enterprise SSO flow allows provisioning or linking accounts with existing users
- Auditing
  - All auth events create audit logs with details; expose a UI panel for admins to review
- RBAC
  - Admins can view/manage roles and permissions; end-user actions limited by assigned roles
- Data Integrity
  - Guard against null/undefined in all data flows; use default values; ensure array operations are guarded

## User Experience Flow

1) Entry
- User lands on UnifiedAuthEntry with options: Sign up, Sign in, Enterprise SSO, or Continue with Social (Google, GitHub, Microsoft)

2) Sign-Up Path
- User selects Sign Up
- Onboarding Wizard: Step 1 (Profile basics), Step 2 (Security & RBAC scope selection), Step 3 (Permissions & Modules), Step 4 (Onboarding tasks), Step 5 (Review & Create)
- User provides email, password (validated strength), accepts terms
- System stores user with emailVerified=false; sends verification email
- User verifies email via link; UI shows verification success or failure with guidance
- User is signed in (session created) and navigated to UserProfilePage or first-time onboarding dashboard

3) Sign-In Path
- User chooses email/password or Social OAuth/SSO
- If email/password:
  - Validate credentials; on success, issue access/refresh tokens; set secure cookies or store tokens safely
  - Load user profile, RBAC roles, and navigate to Home/Dashboard
- If social OAuth:
  - Redirect to provider; upon callback, link or create user; provision RBAC roles if needed
  - Sign in and redirect to profile/dashboard
- If Enterprise SSO:
  - Redirect to IdP; after successful assertion, provision user account or link with existing one; sign in

4) Password Reset
- User requests reset via Email field
- System sends time-limited link/token
- User clicks link, lands on PasswordResetPage; enters new password with strength checks
- Password updated; user logged in and redirected

5) Email Verification
- User receives verification email with token link
- User clicks link; system marks email as verified
- If verification fails (expired/used), show error state with retry guidance

6) Profile & Security
- User navigates to Profile: edit personal info, connect integrations
- Enable/disable 2FA; scan QR code to set up TOTP
- Manage API keys; create/revoke as needed
- View billing summary and manage module preferences
- Review active sessions; revoke any suspicious sessions

7) Admin & Auditing
- Admins access RBAC panels to adjust roles/permissions
- All auth-related actions appear in AuditLog with details
- Admins can review run artifacts and inter-agent traces if relevant

8) Error States
- Clear error messages with retry options
- Guidance for 2FA backup codes, account recovery, or contacting support

## Technical Specifications

Data Models (Schema Details)
- User: id: UUID, email, passwordHash, name, emailVerified boolean, locale, createdAt, updatedAt, lastSignInAt, active boolean
- UserProfile: userId FK, phone, avatarUrl
- Session: id, userId, jwtId, createdAt, expiresAt, lastUsedAt, userAgent, ip, deviceInfo
- RefreshToken: id, token, userId, jwtId, createdAt, expiresAt, revoked boolean
- 2FA: userId, secret, enabled boolean, recoveryCodes[]
- PasswordResetToken: id, userId, token, expiresAt, used boolean
- EmailVerificationToken: id, userId, token, expiresAt, used boolean
- AuditLog: id, userId, action, resource, timestamp, details JSON
- ApiKey: id, userId, key, name, createdAt, lastUsedAt, enabled boolean
- Role: id, name, permissions string[], scope
- Permission: id, name, resource

API Endpoints (Routes & Methods)
- POST /auth/signup
- POST /auth/login
- POST /auth/logout
- POST /auth/refresh
